00:00:10.210 --> 00:00:15.349
The topics are: doing problems on finding
perpendicular distance of a point from line

00:00:15.349 --> 00:00:18.880
and we will be finding equations of a line
perpendicular to two lines given.

00:00:18.880 --> 00:00:27.870
These are small topics but as in other maths
topics, you should learn the approach to solve

00:00:27.870 --> 00:00:28.870
problems like these.

00:00:28.870 --> 00:00:33.910
Let us start by finding perpendicular distance
of a point from a line.

00:00:33.910 --> 00:00:35.870
We have a line given.

00:00:35.870 --> 00:00:43.010
Let us saw we have point A, and that is a_vector,
and we have been given b_vector, which is

00:00:43.010 --> 00:00:44.470
the parallel vector.

00:00:44.470 --> 00:00:49.670
And we have been given a point P. Let us call
it p_vector.

00:00:49.670 --> 00:00:54.479
And we have been asked to find the perpendicular
distance of the point from the line.

00:00:54.479 --> 00:00:58.999
You may recall these kind of problems in 2D
in straight lines.

00:00:58.999 --> 00:01:02.430
But now its 3D or 3-Dimensinal Geometry.

00:01:02.430 --> 00:01:05.030
So how will we solve this problem?

00:01:05.030 --> 00:01:13.270
One of the approaches to start this to think
that there is a point C here, let us call

00:01:13.270 --> 00:01:14.270
it c_vector.

00:01:14.270 --> 00:01:15.550
And the idea is that we know,

00:01:15.550 --> 00:01:18.680
c_vector=a_vector + \lambda b_vector

00:01:18.680 --> 00:01:24.680
because this point is on the line.

00:01:24.680 --> 00:01:30.760
And, PC_vector is perpendicular to b_vector.

00:01:30.760 --> 00:01:31.800
This is what we know, right?

00:01:31.800 --> 00:01:37.590
These are the two conditions we know for the
PC_vector to be perpendicular to the parallel

00:01:37.590 --> 00:01:41.590
vector because this is perpendicular to the
line, so it has to be perpendicular to the

00:01:41.590 --> 00:01:43.270
parallel vector.

00:01:43.270 --> 00:01:48.310
It should flash to you that the condition
of perpendicularity it PC_vector \dot b_vector

00:01:48.310 --> 00:01:49.310
= 0.

00:01:49.310 --> 00:01:51.620
Again, the knowledge of vectors is super critical
in this chapter.

00:01:51.620 --> 00:01:54.650
I have emphasized that many times in the last
two videos also.

00:01:54.650 --> 00:01:58.630
PC_vector is nothing but c_vector - p_vector.

00:01:58.630 --> 00:02:04.810
Thus, c_vector-p_vector \dot b_vector = 0.

00:02:04.810 --> 00:02:19.150
And c_vector is nothing but (a_vector + \lambda
b_vector - p_vector) \dot b =0.

00:02:19.150 --> 00:02:31.020
If you were to find the value of \lambda,
you will get, \lambda = ( (p_vector - a_vector)

00:02:31.020 --> 00:02:35.000
\dot b_vector, divided by |b|^2.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:44.000
Now you have got the value of \lambda, so you can calculate the point, and then you can calculate the distance.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:52.900
I hope you are able to understand and follow
what we are doing here. You can solve this

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:57.000
equation using the associative property by
opening the brackets, and rearranging, you get this.

00:02:57.100 --> 00:03:02.000
Let us do a problem on this so that you can
quickly understand.

00:03:02.100 --> 00:03:33.000
You have been given P=(1,2,3). And the line
is (x-6)/3 = (y-7)/2 = (z-7)/(-2).

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:44.000
How will we find \lambda? I will suggest
you to remember this but you may want to derive it in the paper.

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:47.800
It is up to you. I will recommend
you to remember this, it is

00:03:47.880 --> 00:03:52.050
very easy to remember ( (p_vector - a_vector)
\dot b_vector ) / |b_vector|^2.

00:03:52.050 --> 00:04:02.000
Here,
p_vector = i_cap + 2j_cap+ 3k_cap

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:24.000
a_vector = 6i_cap + 7j_cap+ 7k_cap
b_vector = 3i_cap + 2j_cap - 2k_cap

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:28.660
If I were to find \lambda here, this would
become

00:04:28.660 --> 00:04:46.150
p_vector - a_vector is -5i - 5j - 4k \dot
with 3i + 2j -2k

00:04:46.150 --> 00:04:50.460
( (p_vector - a_vector) \dot b_vector ) / |b_vector|^2.

00:04:50.460 --> 00:04:59.090
|b_vector|^2 = 3^2 + 2^2 + 2^2 = 8 + 9 = 17.

00:04:59.090 --> 00:05:10.070
If you will do this, this will become: -15-10+8
= -17.

00:05:10.070 --> 00:05:16.120
Thus \lambda = -1.

00:05:16.120 --> 00:05:35.169
The point c_vector = a_vector - b_vector,
and it comes out to be, 3i_cap + 5j_cap +

00:05:35.169 --> 00:05:36.600
9k_cap.

00:05:36.600 --> 00:05:52.300
And the distance |PC| = (2^2+3^2+6^2)^(1/2)
= 7.

00:05:52.300 --> 00:06:01.790
You know the vector PC now, so you can find
the distance by taking the sum of x_component^2,

00:06:01.790 --> 00:06:07.310
y_component^2 and z_component^2, and that
comes out to be 7.

00:06:07.310 --> 00:06:12.180
And I hope that is very obvious for you to
solve these types of problems. If you are

00:06:12.180 --> 00:06:16.850
still not very comfortable, please practice.
Just make some problems yourself, make an

00:06:16.850 --> 00:06:22.290
equation of a line, find a point, and then
do the problem. It is very easy. If you do

00:06:22.290 --> 00:06:25.750
this several times, it should be quick for
you to remember.

00:06:25.750 --> 00:06:38.919
Let me give you one more HW problem so that
you can do it on your own. And the HW problem

00:06:38.919 --> 00:06:41.620
is:

00:06:41.620 --> 00:06:58.880
Find a point on y_axis such that

00:06:58.880 --> 00:07:16.290
